1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:16,486
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudansa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudansa

2
00:00:17,378 --> 00:00:26,269
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambhu dasa.

3
00:00:27,010 --> 00:00:31,236
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:32,298 --> 00:00:33,658
Excuse me, I'm out of voice.

5
00:00:34,359 --> 00:00:35,621
I've not been talking for a while.

6
00:00:36,682 --> 00:00:37,884
It's all gone husky.

7
00:00:39,451 --> 00:00:42,875
Okay, so tonight we're going to have a look at this forgiveness.

8
00:00:42,954 --> 00:00:45,357
Most of you, I'm sure, have done exercises on this.

9
00:00:46,399 --> 00:00:50,563
So I'll just go through the basics and then we'll practice it.

10
00:00:52,325 --> 00:01:00,234
So I think there are two fundamental attitudes which really inform all our virtues.

11
00:01:00,274 --> 00:01:02,877
The first one is gratitude.

12
00:01:03,345 --> 00:01:14,540
Once we realize we cannot pay back what we've actually received, our life from our mother and father, et cetera, et cetera, then, of course, it moves you.

13
00:01:15,162 --> 00:01:16,623
You want to give something back.

14
00:01:16,784 --> 00:01:22,150
So it moves to all those qualities of love, compassion, generosity, et cetera.

15
00:01:23,612 --> 00:01:25,695
And forgiveness is the other one.

16
00:01:25,835 --> 00:01:32,745
That's dealing with all the dark side, all the guilt, the shame,

17
00:01:32,962 --> 00:01:36,826
the unforgivingness, all that sort of stuff.

18
00:01:36,846 --> 00:01:43,496
So with these two fundamental or basic attitudes, I think we can have a happy life.

19
00:01:45,760 --> 00:02:02,884
So the first thing to reckon, the first time to remind ourselves is that all the emotions we suffer around forgiving, trying to forgive somebody, being forgiven, asking for forgiveness and forgiving ourselves,

20
00:02:03,471 --> 00:02:06,436
All the emotional stuff, remember, is all self-made.

21
00:02:07,216 --> 00:02:13,085
So, you know, when somebody says something that is a bit nasty, our response is our response.

22
00:02:13,125 --> 00:02:14,366
They didn't cause that.

23
00:02:14,387 --> 00:02:16,469
So that's the first thing to remind ourselves.

24
00:02:16,669 --> 00:02:19,774
All the stuff we're going to work with has been made by me.

25
00:02:21,856 --> 00:02:27,985
And the idea, of course, is to undermine them and then they will transform naturally.

26
00:02:28,425 --> 00:02:30,187
So that's the other thing we have to remember is

27
00:02:30,487 --> 00:02:34,996
All negative states will eventually transform themselves to the opposite.

28
00:02:35,657 --> 00:02:36,618
Nothing is lost.

29
00:02:36,639 --> 00:02:38,902
Where there's hatred, there'll be love, and so on.

30
00:02:40,846 --> 00:02:44,872
And the final note on this is, it's for us.

31
00:02:45,052 --> 00:02:47,217
So forgiveness is for us, it's not for them.

32
00:02:49,039 --> 00:02:53,608
Which might sound a bit selfish, but they've also got the same problem with us, right?

33
00:02:53,688 --> 00:02:55,651
So whatever we're doing here now,

34
00:02:55,835 --> 00:03:01,102
asking for forgiveness, forgiving, etc., they also have their own problems.

35
00:03:01,883 --> 00:03:06,588
And when they're doing forgiveness practice, they're doing it just for themselves.

36
00:03:07,028 --> 00:03:17,883
So it's basically a practice for our own benefit, if the other person, to say, is affected by it, all well and good.

37
00:03:18,063 --> 00:03:20,627
So for instance, if we apologize to somebody,

38
00:03:20,606 --> 00:03:24,330
and they feel the heart to respond, that's good.

39
00:03:24,731 --> 00:03:28,235
We've been a catalyst for their movement, their heart movement.

40
00:03:28,816 --> 00:03:31,840
But of course, they don't have to forgive.

41
00:03:32,300 --> 00:03:34,782
That's sometimes difficult to accept.

42
00:03:37,646 --> 00:03:39,187
The next thing is about attitudes.

43
00:03:39,489 --> 00:03:41,191
So these are sankharas.

44
00:03:41,311 --> 00:03:43,693
Most of you know that word, sankhara.

45
00:03:43,712 --> 00:03:46,817
It's normally translated as volitional conditions.

46
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:56,001
which doesn't mean very much, but it's basically the choices we make, the habits we have, which are conditioned and conditioning.

47
00:03:56,382 --> 00:03:57,223
That's the important thing.

48
00:03:57,943 --> 00:04:01,087
So these are energetic conditionings.

49
00:04:01,908 --> 00:04:09,057
And the way I think of them is like they're balloons of particular types of reactivity.

50
00:04:09,173 --> 00:04:15,625
So, I might, for instance, be very annoyed when people are late, okay?

51
00:04:15,645 --> 00:04:19,391
So, every time somebody's late, I get irritated, right?

52
00:04:19,411 --> 00:04:21,194
And I don't look at it, I don't think about it.

53
00:04:21,214 --> 00:04:26,363
So, this balloon of irritation around people being late grows and grows and grows.

54
00:04:26,685 --> 00:04:29,410
And then one day, somebody's too late.

55
00:04:30,132 --> 00:04:42,521
And it's like a pin touches this balloon and all this irritation and anger just burst out and that's where you get this rage, this road rage and all the stuff we hear about.

56
00:04:42,540 --> 00:04:48,815
So what we're doing is we're letting the steam, we're letting the bad air out of that balloon.

57
00:04:50,567 --> 00:04:53,091
Okay, so there are three subjects, obviously.

58
00:04:53,932 --> 00:05:01,002
We have to make the ability to ask for forgiveness easy for ourselves.

59
00:05:01,502 --> 00:05:04,386
It's against our pride, you know, but we have to make it easy.

60
00:05:05,206 --> 00:05:06,889
And then we have to ask for forgiveness.

61
00:05:07,108 --> 00:05:08,791
That's also something we don't like doing.

62
00:05:09,713 --> 00:05:15,019
And then finally, we've got to forgive ourselves, which is often the most difficult.

63
00:05:16,982 --> 00:05:18,363
Now,

64
00:05:18,630 --> 00:05:30,865
The process is we remember something and we have an event and that event carries with it all the loadings that we put on it, the hurt, the anger, etc.

65
00:05:31,526 --> 00:05:33,430
So the event comes to mind.

66
00:05:33,709 --> 00:05:38,495
Now, we have to be careful, really careful it doesn't shoot up into a fantasy.

67
00:05:38,661 --> 00:05:44,129
Once we're up there in the clouds fantasizing, whether we like it or not, we're making things worse.

68
00:05:44,870 --> 00:05:53,240
Whatever that emotion is, it's being exercised and made worse by storytelling.

69
00:05:53,261 --> 00:05:56,185
So as soon as we see that happening, we just come back.

70
00:05:56,805 --> 00:05:59,730
And we try to hold that frame fairly still.

71
00:06:01,752 --> 00:06:06,237
And while we're doing that, the attention, of course, is drawn to what's coming from the heart.

72
00:06:06,742 --> 00:06:08,404
So what might come up is hurt.

73
00:06:08,685 --> 00:06:10,829
See, somebody said something, so hurt.

74
00:06:11,651 --> 00:06:14,857
And the next protocol is how we're relating to this hurt.

75
00:06:15,759 --> 00:06:19,386
Now, we don't like to accept that because it's against our pride.

76
00:06:20,307 --> 00:06:28,783
So we have to allow that aversion, that not wanting to disappear until we can allow the heart to express its hurt completely.

77
00:06:29,151 --> 00:06:29,733
Right.

78
00:06:29,752 --> 00:06:31,416
That's the healing process.

79
00:06:31,437 --> 00:06:37,572
So we're using this little image that we've got, this event to get in touch with the hurt.

80
00:06:37,831 --> 00:06:39,235
Right.

81
00:06:39,254 --> 00:06:48,156
And that hurt, of course, is connected to all the hurts that we have, just like the anger in that balloon is connected to all the other angers.

82
00:06:48,288 --> 00:06:53,454
And as we let out one little bit of anger, everything else is affected, right?

83
00:06:53,475 --> 00:06:54,576
So it's systemic.

84
00:06:54,817 --> 00:06:59,742
Everything we do has a systemic effect on our own hearts and minds.

85
00:07:02,987 --> 00:07:09,755
Now, when we're doing this, by the way, as you come, say, to forgive somebody, you can't do it.

86
00:07:10,461 --> 00:07:12,644
Fine, you don't worry about that at all.

87
00:07:12,906 --> 00:07:28,968
You just keep working on the hurt and then eventually the heart softens and you can do it Okay, and we always start with a bit of meta just to warm the heart up a bit and then we We ask for forgiveness.

88
00:07:29,290 --> 00:07:37,482
We forgive others and then we forgive ourselves Now when we're asking for forgiveness and

89
00:07:38,389 --> 00:07:44,197
The first thing that might come up is the reason why the person did it.

90
00:07:45,879 --> 00:07:50,906
And so you've got to be aware of that relationship you have to the person.

91
00:07:51,567 --> 00:07:53,850
But basically, you're looking at the hurt.

92
00:07:54,872 --> 00:08:01,139
And when that passes, perhaps the desire of revenge, and you have to let that go too.

93
00:08:20,829 --> 00:08:22,571
Yeah, I'm just scrolling through here.

94
00:08:35,562 --> 00:08:37,604
I seem to have lost something here.

95
00:08:41,788 --> 00:08:50,414
Okay, when it comes to forgiving, when it comes to forgiving, that's the next bit we're doing.

96
00:08:50,985 --> 00:08:55,832
Again, there's that hardness that's in the heart.

97
00:08:55,893 --> 00:08:56,995
It doesn't want to forgive.

98
00:08:57,836 --> 00:08:59,638
And there's a story here.

99
00:09:00,458 --> 00:09:12,476
You know, when the Islamist blew himself up in London, this is going back a bit, there was an Anglican priest that left the order saying she couldn't carry out the ministry because she couldn't forgive the bomber who'd killed her daughter.

100
00:09:13,197 --> 00:09:16,302
But it's actually never a case of can't, it's a case of won't.

101
00:09:16,788 --> 00:09:23,554
And let's just hope that distraught mother has found a way eventually to open up her heart.

102
00:09:24,456 --> 00:09:33,144
And of course, if we look around the world at this moment, there must be a lot of mothers who are utterly distraught at what's happened to their children, young and old.

103
00:09:34,245 --> 00:09:45,376
But then you get a story like the mother who went to see her son's murderer and finally took him home when he was let out of prison and treated him like her son.

104
00:09:45,727 --> 00:09:50,596
So we have to remember that to forgive somebody is not to try and forget something.

105
00:09:50,635 --> 00:09:52,799
That's, of course, as we know, is suppressive.

106
00:09:53,900 --> 00:09:56,765
We're just trying to release the emotional charge.

107
00:09:57,727 --> 00:10:01,413
Sometimes when we do that, we feel we're condoning what they do.

108
00:10:01,433 --> 00:10:02,775
But that's not so.

109
00:10:02,936 --> 00:10:04,739
That's just wrong feeling.

110
00:10:06,181 --> 00:10:07,803
We're sort of letting them off.

111
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:13,905
But obviously where amends and compensation is needed, definitely we should ask for it.

112
00:10:14,025 --> 00:10:24,037
And especially where there's justice, you know, where we need justice for grievous bodily harm, rape, all that dreadful stuff, which I hope none of you have suffered from.

113
00:10:25,018 --> 00:10:31,985
But then, of course, you have to seek justice, but not with that anger, not with that desire for vengeance.

114
00:10:36,235 --> 00:10:39,840
And of course, sometimes you have to stay away from people who harmed us.

115
00:10:40,260 --> 00:10:41,743
You know, you have to protect yourself.

116
00:10:42,323 --> 00:10:43,205
That's not a problem.

117
00:10:45,128 --> 00:10:47,250
And then finally, forgiving ourselves.

118
00:10:47,370 --> 00:10:49,193
So forgiving ourselves.

119
00:10:50,635 --> 00:10:56,004
There are two contemplations that are really helpful.

120
00:10:56,024 --> 00:10:58,006
First one is dependence origination.

121
00:10:58,966 --> 00:11:06,654
So remember, in dependent origination, we start off with abhija, this ignorance, which produces a delusive idea about the world.

122
00:11:07,576 --> 00:11:11,100
And it's really based along the idea of a self.

123
00:11:11,120 --> 00:11:13,182
And we're trying to seek happiness in the world.

124
00:11:13,982 --> 00:11:17,486
And we do it in this way that creates suffering.

125
00:11:18,469 --> 00:11:25,817
And as we practice, we can see the cause, the psychological cause of that, which is the desire, the wrong desire.

126
00:11:26,152 --> 00:11:30,337
And the fact that we're holding on to things which are impermanent, it doesn't make sense.

127
00:11:30,798 --> 00:11:38,870
And eventually, to undermine that whole concept of a self we have, it's a feeling concept, it's not just a head concept.

128
00:11:40,051 --> 00:11:42,835
And what this does is, of course, it takes us towards wisdom.

129
00:11:43,355 --> 00:11:50,826
So one movement is from ignorance, delusion, and then the process of insight, which takes us to wisdom.

130
00:11:51,464 --> 00:11:57,274
From the heart's point of view, just as the delusion, we cannot be blamed for the delusion.

131
00:11:57,936 --> 00:11:59,398
The ignorance isn't culpable.

132
00:11:59,859 --> 00:12:03,105
So from the heart's point of view, we're never meant to do any harm.

133
00:12:03,666 --> 00:12:07,211
The heart has always been pure in its intentions.

134
00:12:07,394 --> 00:12:17,287
But because of this delusion, it leads itself to being acquisitive, to being aversive, to being fearful, and so on.

135
00:12:17,307 --> 00:12:21,471
So all these, of course, have produced unwholesome actions.

136
00:12:22,352 --> 00:12:26,719
And then there's the consequence of that, which we're dealing with now.

137
00:12:27,154 --> 00:12:28,596
or forgiving this business.

138
00:12:29,778 --> 00:12:34,322
And when all that's purified, we end up with the pure heart, right?

139
00:12:34,341 --> 00:12:40,288
So that's the process from a sort of pure heart to all this negativity.

140
00:12:40,668 --> 00:12:47,315
We work with it and it's basically most, it's the sweat when it comes to the spiritual practice.

141
00:12:47,335 --> 00:12:48,557
The other bit's easy.

142
00:12:48,576 --> 00:12:50,158
The insight's not a problem, is it?

143
00:12:51,099 --> 00:12:55,744
It's just, you know, all the guns in the heart that we're trying to get rid of.

144
00:12:56,129 --> 00:13:01,635
And that leads us to purity, purity, immaculacy, back to purity and immaculacy.

145
00:13:02,577 --> 00:13:06,543
So the Buddha talked about it like, you know, dirt that gets on a cloth.

146
00:13:07,124 --> 00:13:10,849
And when you wash it, the cloth goes back to its original loveliness.

147
00:13:12,951 --> 00:13:16,677
So that's the projection that we're on.

148
00:13:16,836 --> 00:13:18,558
That's what we're doing.

149
00:13:18,943 --> 00:13:20,966
And the other one is about karma.

150
00:13:21,288 --> 00:13:30,662
So that's pretty, I mean, at its simplest equation, you do something which is harmful, some harm will come of it.

151
00:13:31,082 --> 00:13:32,365
You never know what, right?

152
00:13:33,626 --> 00:13:40,658
And remember that the harm, if it's outwardly to what we speak and what we do, you don't know what the effect will be.

153
00:13:40,798 --> 00:13:43,702
It goes into a matrix of relationships, right?

154
00:13:44,138 --> 00:13:47,042
And the same happens to us when we do something.

155
00:13:47,121 --> 00:13:54,831
Every time we say something or do anything, whether it's good or bad, it affects the whole, it's a systemic effect inside us, right?

156
00:13:54,850 --> 00:14:00,759
It affects the whole psychology in some way or other.

157
00:14:00,818 --> 00:14:11,412
So now the bit that I found really relieving was that when we do something wrong, there is a karmic effect.

158
00:14:11,763 --> 00:14:15,067
response to it, there'll be something comes back to it.

159
00:14:15,547 --> 00:14:17,308
And that's all we have to suffer.

160
00:14:18,049 --> 00:14:27,961
All the business about punishment and the way we talk to ourselves and the recrimination, the self-recrimination, the anguish and all that, all that's not necessary.

161
00:14:28,441 --> 00:14:41,095
All that's necessary is to receive the consequence of unwholesome action, just to receive it with patience and bear with it until it also will dry up, pass away.

162
00:14:41,345 --> 00:14:45,892
So that's an interesting reflection, I think, on karma.

163
00:14:46,572 --> 00:14:48,056
So don't feed the critic.

164
00:14:48,196 --> 00:14:52,763
That's the big thing.

165
00:14:52,783 --> 00:14:55,626
Okay.

166
00:14:56,187 --> 00:14:57,630
So we'll do the practice.

167
00:14:58,010 --> 00:14:59,273
We'll do the practice together.

168
00:15:00,534 --> 00:15:08,668
And then I'm going to put what is actually a written piece here as a PDF on the website.

169
00:15:09,086 --> 00:15:19,485
with this video so that if you want you can download it and just look at it and yeah use it yeah

